          "body": "The chapter's indictment proceeds anatomically. Hands and fingers defiled with blood and iniquity (v. 3) — the instruments of physical violence. Lips and tongue speaking falsehood and wickedness (v. 3) — the instruments of social corruption. No honest legal plea, no righteous lawsuit (v. 4) — the courts themselves corrupted. Feet running to evil and hastening to shed innocent blood (v. 7) — the instrument of pursuing sin. Thoughts saturated with iniquity (v. 7) — the source from which all the above flows. Isaiah's catalog is not random; it reads like a deliberate inversion of the wholeness described in Psalm 1 and the deeds of the servant in Isaiah 53. Where the servant of chapters 52-53 bears the people's iniquities without any defilement of his own, the people of chapter 59 are comprehensively defiled in every member. The spider-web and viper-egg images (vv. 5-6) are especially pointed: the work of such people is simultaneously lethal and useless. You cannot eat their eggs without dying; you cannot wear their webs as clothing. All their labor produces nothing protective, nothing nourishing — only poison and death. Calvin noted that this is the condition of all unregenerate human effort: even its most elaborate constructions cannot cover the nakedness they were meant to address."
